The great dispersion stability of corrosion inhibitors is a prerequisite for their employment [23]. There is no precipitation in the solution regardless of the concentration of CDs/CDAs after two weeks of standing at room temperature (Fig. 5
                        ). According to the agglomeration-induced quenching effect [24], the fluorescence will weaken or even disappear if CDs/CDAs agglomerate in the solution. Noticeably, the solutions with CDs/CDAs emit green/blue fluorescence under UV light. And the higher the content of CDs/CDAs, the stronger the fluorescence intensity. The optical behavior of CDAs is akin to that of CDs (Fig. 6
                        ). Specifically, the peak intensities of UV–vis and PL spectra improve with increased addition of CDs/CDAs. Notably, UV–vis and PL spectra of CDs/CDAs in 1 mol/L HCl solution are different compared with the aqueous solution, attributed to the protonation of CDs/CDAs in the acidic solution [25]. More importantly, UV–vis and PL spectra of CDs/CDAs are essentially unchanged after standing for two weeks (Fig. 7
                        ). The above results qualitatively and quantitatively demonstrate that both CDs and CDAs own splendid wonderful long-term dispersion stability in acidic environments.

The carbon steel surface elements consist of C, O, Fe, and N (Table 6
                        ). By comparison with the blank group, the content of C and N elements improves and the content of O and Fe elements reduces after incorporating 200 mg/L CDs/CDAs. Particularly, the CDAs-containing group exhibits greater changes than the CDs-containing group. This expresses that CDAs possess a greater adsorption capacity on the carbon steel surface compared with CDs, thereby reducing the exposed area and the formation of corrosion products. High-resolution O1s spectra (Fig. 14
                        a–c) display two peaks belonging to O2− (530.1 ± 0.1 eV) and OH− (531.4 ± 0.1 eV), respectively [42,43]. High-resolution Fe2p spectra (Fig. 14d–f) reveal four peaks at 707.1 ± 0.1, 710.1 ± 0.5, 711.8 ± 0.4, and 714.1 ± 0.3 eV corresponding to Fe(0), FeO, Fe2O3, and FeOOH, respectively [28,44,45]. Generally, Fe2+ in the passive film possesses better corrosion resistance than Fe3+ [42,46]. That is, the larger the Fe2+/Fe3+ ratio, the greater the protection effect. In the meantime, the OH−/O2− ratio corresponds to the FeOOH/Fe2O3 ratio, and Fe2O3 is more stable and denser than FeOOH [28]. Namely, the lower the OH−/O2− ratio, the stronger the corrosion resistance. In contrast to the blank group, the incorporation of CDs/CDAs increases the ratio of Fe2+/Fe3+ and decreases the ratio of OH−/O2−, demonstrating that CDs/CDAs improve corrosion resistance. Noticeably, the Fe2+/Fe3+ ratio of the 200 mg/L CDAs-containing group (2.43) is greater than that of the CDs-containing group (1.38), and the OH−/O2− ratio of the 200 mg/L CDAs-containing group (1.97) is smaller than that of the CDs-containing group (3.84). This manifests that CDAs are more effective in restraining corrosion by generating a protective iron oxide layer on the carbon steel surface than CDs. High-resolution N1s spectra (Fig. 14g and h) exhibit three peaks assigned to C–N (398.1 ± 0.3 eV), Fe–N (399.9 ± 0.2 eV) and N+H (401.0 ± 0.3 eV), respectively. Specifically, C–N is related to the unprotonated N [47], while N+H is associated with the protonation of N [48]. Fe–N indicates the formation of coordination bonds between N of CDs/CDAs and Fe on the surface of carbon steel [32]. Notably, compared with CDs, CDAs possess a higher Fe–N content, implying a greater adsorption amount on the surface of carbon steel.
